Projecting Fantasy Football Points Using Current Game Status¶

Alec Rowell¶

December 2022¶

1. Introduction¶

1.1 What is Fantasy Football?¶

Fantasy football is an online game for people who watch the NFL in which competitors form leagues (typically of size 8-16) with friends and draft NFL players to compete for them. Each NFL play awards points to fantasy players based on their performance on a given play. There are a few different popular scoring methods, but in this project, I will focus on scoring from a typical "PPR" league, which works as follows:

  • 1 point to the receiver for a reception
  • 0.1 points per receiving yard
  • 0.1 points per rushing yard
  • 6 points for a rushing or receiving touchdown
  • 0.04 points per passing yard
  • 4 points for a passing touchdown

There are a few other ways to gain or lose points (such as fumbling) but for the purposes of this project, I'll stick to the list above. Also, we are only going to be dealing with receivers, running backs, and qbs, so tight ends, defenses and kickers will be excluded.

1.2 Projections¶

To help players make roster decisions, fantasy websites provide a projected point value for each player. As the games are in progress, players can view an updated projection for each player as well as for their whole team in order to see how they are stacking up to their competition. This in-game projection is calculated by dividing the player's original projection by the portion of time left in the game. However, this system is simple and easy to understand but could certainly be improved upon to make it more accurate. Creating a more accurate live projection is the intent of the project.

2. Acquiring Data¶

2.1 nfl-data-py¶

For the majority of the data in this project, I will be using a Python package called nfl-data-py. Information about this dataset can be found at https://pypi.org/project/nfl-data-py/.
This package is a way to access data from multiple previously collected datasets as outlined on the page above. It will make it very easy for us to access and manipulate most of our data. To begin, I will be importing their table for general team descriptions for visualizations, the table for rosters, and as the play-by-play data from 2012-2021 which I will use for the majority of our analysis.

3. Data Processing¶

3.1 Fantasy Points per Play¶

Now that we have a large amount of raw play by play data, we need to reorganize it somewhat so that we can use it for our visualizations and models. The first step will be to use the data from each play to calculate how many fantasy points were earned on that play. We have two cases for each play:

  • Rushing play: points are only awarded to a rusher
  • Passing play: points are awarded to both the passer and the receiver
    Let's create new columns called 'fpts_{position}' that will hold this information per play.
In [11]:
pbp['fpts_rusher'] = pbp['rushing_yards'] * 0.1 # 0.1 points per rushing yard
pbp['fpts_receiver'] = pbp['receiving_yards'] * 0.1 + 1 # 0.1 points per receiving yard + 1 point per reception
pbp['fpts_passer'] = pbp['passing_yards'] * 0.04 # 0.04 points per passing yard
pbp.loc[pbp['rush_touchdown'] == 1, 'fpts_rusher'] += 6 # 6 points per rushing touchdown
pbp.loc[pbp['pass_touchdown'] == 1, 'fpts_receiver'] += 6 # 6 points per receiving touchdown
pbp.loc[pbp['pass_touchdown'] == 1, 'fpts_passer'] += 4 # 4 points per passing touchdown

3.2 Game-wise Fantasy Points¶

Now we need to calculate the total fantasy points earned by each player in each game. We are going to keep track of the top 3 receivers, 2 running backs, and 1 quarterback for each team since these are more or less the only fantasy relevant players in each game. This calculation is somewhat convoluted and very resource intensive since we have to iterate over every row in the dataframe. However, it is certainly necessary for this project, so we will proceed as follows:
For each game, we:

  1. Initialize a dicionary for each recorded position (wr1-3, rb1-2, and qb1) for each team
  2. For each play:
    1. Find which team has the ball
    2. Identify the players that received fantasy points
    3. Add the fantasy points to their id in the dictionary
  3. Sort the dictionaries to find the top 3 receivers, top 2 running backs, and top quarterback for each team
  4. Add these players' ids and total points in the game to our dataframe
In [13]:
def get_position (player_id, season):
  unique_list = rosters.loc[(rosters['player_id'] == player_id) &
            (rosters['season'] == season)]['position'].unique() # Should be only value
  if len(unique_list) > 0: # Make sure there is at least one value, returns None otherwise
    return unique_list[0]
  else:
    return None

def get_player_name(player_id):
  unique_list = rosters.loc[(rosters['player_id'] == player_id)]['player_name'].unique() # Should be only value
  if len(unique_list) > 0: # Make sure there is at least one value, returns None otherwise
    return unique_list[0]
  else:
    return None

total_games = len(pbp['old_game_id'].unique())
i = 0
for game_id in pbp['old_game_id'].unique(): # iterates over every game in pbp
  i += 1
  if i % 100 == 0:
    print(f'{i} / {total_games} games done')
  home_wrs = defaultdict(int) # Initialize dictionaries with default value of 0
  home_rbs = defaultdict(int)
  home_qbs = defaultdict(int)
  away_wrs = defaultdict(int)
  away_rbs = defaultdict(int)
  away_qbs = defaultdict(int)

  # utility function: picks correct dictionary and adds fpts to the correct key
  def add_points(player_id, season, fpts, home_team):
    pos = get_position(player_id, season) # Finds position from roster table
    # Updates appropriate dictionary
    if pos:
      if pos == 'WR':
        if home_team:
          home_wrs[player_id] += fpts
        else:
          away_wrs[player_id] += fpts
      elif pos == 'RB':
        if home_team:
          home_rbs[player_id] += fpts
        else:
          away_rbs[player_id] += fpts
      elif pos == 'QB':
        if home_team:
          home_qbs[player_id] += fpts
        else:
          away_qbs[player_id] += fpts

  # iterates over each play in the game
  for index, play in pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id].iterrows():
    home_team = False
    if play['posteam'] == play['home_team']: # Finds home/away to pass into add_points
      home_team = True

    # Calls add_points for each type of points gained on the play
    if not pd.isnull(play['rusher_player_id']):
      add_points(play['rusher_player_id'], play['season'],
                 play['fpts_rusher'], home_team)
    elif not pd.isnull(play['receiver_player_id']):
      add_points(play['receiver_player_id'], play['season'],
                 play['fpts_receiver'], home_team)
    elif not pd.isnull(play['passer_player_id']):
      add_points(play['passer_player_id'], play['season'],
                 play['fpts_passer'], home_team)

  # sort each dictionary
  home_wrs = sorted(home_wrs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
  home_rbs = sorted(home_rbs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
  home_qbs = sorted(home_qbs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
  away_wrs = sorted(away_wrs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
  away_rbs = sorted(away_rbs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
  away_qbs = sorted(away_qbs.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)

  # update appropriate fields in pbp
  if len(home_wrs) >= 1:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_wr1']] = home_wrs[0][0] # Set wr1 id
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_wr1_total_pts']] = round(home_wrs[0][1], 2) # Set wr1 points
  if len(home_wrs) >= 2:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_wr2']] = home_wrs[1][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_wr2_total_pts']] = round(home_wrs[1][1], 2)
  if len(home_wrs) >= 3:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_wr3']] = home_wrs[2][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_wr3_total_pts']] = round(home_wrs[2][1], 2)

  if len(home_rbs) >= 1:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_rb1']] = home_rbs[0][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_rb1_total_pts']] = round(home_rbs[0][1], 2)
  if len(home_rbs) >= 2:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_rb2']] = home_rbs[1][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_rb2_total_pts']] = round(home_rbs[1][1], 2)

  if len(home_qbs) >= 1:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['home_qb']] = home_qbs[0][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['home_qb_total_pts']] = round(home_qbs[0][1], 2)

  # Now repeat for away team

  if len(away_wrs) >= 1:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['away_wr1']] = away_wrs[0][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['away_wr1_total_pts']] = round(away_wrs[0][1], 2)
  if len(away_wrs) >= 2:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['away_wr2']] = away_wrs[1][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['away_wr2_total_pts']] = round(away_wrs[1][1], 2)
  if len(away_wrs) >= 3:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['away_wr3']] = away_wrs[2][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['away_wr3_total_pts']] = round(away_wrs[2][1], 2)

  if len(away_rbs) >= 1:
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id, ['away_rb1']] = away_rbs[0][0]
    pbp.loc[pbp['old_game_id'] == game_id,
            ['away_rb1_total_pts']] = round(away_rbs[0][1], 2)
  if len(away_rbs) >= 2:

3.3 Current Fantasy Points¶

Now that we have identified the relevant players in each game, we can find those players' current fantasy score after each play.
In these next few calculations, we are going to make use of pandas' groupby function, about which you can find more information here: https://realpython.com/pandas-groupby/

In [15]:
# Iterate over each combination of home/away and position (total of 12)
for side in ['home', 'away']:
  for pos in ['wr1', 'wr2', 'wr3', 'rb1', 'rb2', 'qb']:
    pbp[f'{side}_{pos}_pts'] = 0
    for pts_type in ['receiver', 'rusher', 'passer']:
      # Adds a new column '{side}_{pos}_pts' for respective fantasy points on each play
      pbp.loc[pbp[f'{pts_type}_player_id'] == pbp[f'{side}_{pos}'], f'{side}_{pos}_pts'] += pbp[f'fpts_{pts_type}']

# Iterate over each combination of home/away and position (total of 12)
for side in ['home', 'away']:
  for pos in ['wr1', 'wr2', 'wr3', 'rb1', 'rb2', 'qb']:
    # Takes the cumulative sum of per play fantasy points grouped by the game id to find the current fantasy score
    pbp[f'{side}_{pos}_curr_pts'] = pbp.groupby('old_game_id')[f'{side}_{pos}_pts'].cumsum()
    # Sets the total points to the final value of curr_pts
    pbp[f'{side}_{pos}_total_pts'] = pbp.groupby('old_game_id')[f'{side}_{pos}_curr_pts'].transform(lambda x: x.iloc[-1])

3.6 Point Differential¶

To make our models easier, we will also create a column called posteam_diff, which is the current differential of the possession team, so it is positive if the posession team is winning and negative if the possession team is losing.

In [19]:
# Add column 'posteam_diff' = the score differential for the team with posession
# If positive, the team with the ball is winning
pbp.loc[pbp['posteam'] == pbp['home_team'], 'posteam_diff'] = \
  pbp['total_home_score'] - pbp['total_away_score']
pbp.loc[pbp['posteam'] == pbp['away_team'], 'posteam_diff'] = \
  pbp['total_away_score'] - pbp['total_home_score']

# Add column 'home_diff' = the score differential for the winning team
# If positive, the home team is winning
pbp['home_diff'] = pbp['total_home_score'] - pbp['total_away_score']

3.7 Posteam is Home¶

Another easy column to add that will be helpful is whether or not the team with possession is the home team.

In [20]:
pbp['home_pos'] = 0 # Initialize to 0 (false)
pbp.loc[pbp['posteam'] == pbp['home_team'], 'home_pos'] = 1 # If the home team has possession, change to 1 (true)

4.4 Fantasy Points, Minutes Remaining, and Winning vs Losing¶

A commonly known trend in football games is that as time dwindles down, losing teams tend to pass more while winning teams tend to run more. This occurs because passing plays take less time than rushing plays, so in order to catch up, the losing team wants to minimize time wasted, and thus should pass more.

To see this, we are going to have to analyze the interaction of two independent variables: time remaining and game score. This is not possible on our previous 2-d plots, so we are going to add a third dimension by separating the plots into when the teams are losing vs when they are winning.

In [26]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(12, 18))
fig.suptitle('Fantasy Points vs Minutes Remaining by Position and Winning/Losing')

# Invert the x axis since it is time remaining, so the game goes from left to right
# Use pbp.loc[pbp['posteam_diff'] >= 0] to find when teams are winning

# Since a team scoring very early does not happen often

Finally, a clear correlation! We can see clearly that as time remaining decreases:

  • Receiving and passing fantasy points decrease for the winning team
  • Receiving and passing fantasy points increase for the losing team
  • Rushing fantasy points increase for the winning team
  • Rushing fantasy points decrease for the losing team

It is important to note that these correlations are not linear, as the main difference only comes twoards the end of the game.

However, this insight should be enough for us to build a model to beat the current system that does not take this interaction into account.

Our model is likely to pick up other interactions between variables that are even more difficult to find through this basic data exploration.

5 Model Fitting¶

To evaluate our models, we will be using Mean Squared Error (MSE), which is equal to the mean of (predicted value - actual value)^2 over our test set. We have chosen mean squared error in order to harsly punish predictions that are very far off from the actual value. By minimizing MSE, we can feel confident that we have an improvement in accuracy.

In place of projections, we will using total points, since that represents perfectly accurate pregame predictions.

5.1 Wide Receivers¶

5.1.1 Preparing Training and Test Sets¶

One last step before we can actually create our models, we need to divide our data into a training set and a test set. This is necessary because it would not be fair to test our model on data that it trained on. We will also split it up into x and y, where x is our input data, which is only what is available during the game. Y is the points remaining, which is what we are trying to predict with our projections.

5.1.2 Current Model¶

Let's first calculate our baseline of the current projections model.

The current model is simply: projected points * (time remaining / total game time)

Let's calculate the mean absolute error for this system in our test set (The 2021 season)

In [28]:
# MSE = mean((actual - projected)^2)
mse = ((y_test_wr - X_test_wr['wr_total_pts'] * (X_test_wr['game_seconds_remaining'] / 3600))**2).mean()
print(f'MSE = {mse}')

MSE = 8.639789613326784

5.1.3 K-Nearest Neighbor¶

The first model we will try is a regression model called k-nearest neighbor. More information can be found about it here:

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/neighbors.html#regression

It takes a hyperparameter of n, which is the number of close points that it will take into account when making its prediction. Let's try a few different values of n and combine their MSE to find a sweet spot for the parameter.

In [29]:
for n in [5, 10, 20, 50]:
  # Create Knn object with appropriate value for n
  knn = neighbors.KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors = n)
  # Fit model
  knn.fit(X_train_wr, y_train_wr)

  # Use model projection to calculate MSE on our test set
  mse = ((knn.predict(X_test_wr) - y_test_wr)**2).mean()
  print(f'MSE for n={n}: {mse}')

MSE for n=5: 9.156399697892903
MSE for n=10: 8.4660452326216
MSE for n=20: 8.211178668815393
MSE for n=50: 8.324530750300902

Looks like n=20 is a good bet for this model, and we can see that it did indeed improve on the MSE of the base model. However, I think we can do better. Let's try another regression model.

5.1.4 Decision Tree Regressor¶

Another popular model is a decision tree regressor, which you can read about here:

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/tree.html#tree

Let's see what it can manage for our data.

In [30]:
# Create regressor object random_state to ensure consitent results
dtr = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state = 0)
# Fit model
dtr.fit(X_train_wr, y_train_wr)

# Use model projection to calculate MSE on our test set
mse = ((dtr.predict(X_test_wr) - y_test_wr)**2).mean()
print(f'MSE = {mse}')

MSE = 14.823069889897978

That's much worse than the current system! Not much more to say than that. Let's move on to another model.

5.1.5 Linear Regression with Interaction Terms¶

For our next model, we will use another package called statsmodels, which provides a function called ols, which allows us to perform a linear regression with whichever terms we choose. Here we are going to use all possible interaction terms between our columns. To accomplish this, we will use an R-style formula in our method call. As the number of columns increases, these interactions can get out of hand very quickly. However, since we are only analyzing 5 columns, it is still reasonable to look at all of the interactions.

Read more about:

  • OLS: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/generated/statsmodels.formula.api.ols.html
  • R-style formulas: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/example_formulas.html

The summary features prints out a ton of information about our model, so let's focus on some highlights:

  • This is far more linear regression terms than normal, but it is helpful here because it allows the algorithm to identify correlations that we might not see through typical data exploration.
  • You can see which interaction terms we are confident about a relationship in by the column p > |t|, which is more or less the probability of a significant correlation between that interaction and our results.

  • There is a warning on the bottom about multicollinearity. It is likely that this is due to our interaction terms, but let's run a test to make sure none of our initial columns are at fault.

5.1.6 Hypothesis Test¶

Our mean squared error seamed significantly better, but let's run a statistical test to ensure that the difference was statistically significant. To do this, we'll use the t test function another key Python library: scipy. We are using a t test since we want to compare the sample mean squared errors from our test data.

In [34]:
# Make list of residuals from OLS
ols_errors = y_test_wr - wr_ols.predict(X_test_wr)
# Make list of residuals from base projection model
base_errors = y_test_wr - X_test_wr['wr_total_pts'] * (X_test_wr['game_seconds_remaining'] / 3600)
# Perform a t-test for the above lists squared
stats.ttest_ind(ols_errors**2, base_errors**2)
Out[34]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-22.624864341469962, pvalue=2.7956032430211804e-113)

A p-value that small eliminates all doubt that we were successful in creating a new model for in-game fantasy projections.

The following sections will be replicas of the previous process with respect to running backs and quarterbacks (Spoilers: similarly successful results). If you are not interested in this, skip to the conclusion.

5.2 Running Backs¶

5.2.1 Preparing Training and Test Sets¶

One last step before we can actually create our models, we need to divide our data into a training set and a test set. This is necessary because it would not be fair to test our model on data that it trained on. We will also split it up into x and y, where x is our input data, which is only what is available during the game. Y is the points remaining, which is what we are trying to predict with our projections.

To do this, we'll use the t test function another key Python library: scipy. We are using a t test since we want to compare the sample mean squared errors from our test data.

In [39]:
# Same process as above but for rbs
ols_errors = y_test_rb - rb_ols.predict(X_test_rb)
base_errors = y_test_rb - X_test_rb['rb_total_pts'] * (X_test_rb['game_seconds_remaining'] / 3600)
stats.ttest_ind(ols_errors**2, base_errors**2)
Out[39]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-15.574797913518285, pvalue=1.1265796067493718e-54)

A p-value that small eliminates all doubt that we were successful in creating a new model for in-game fantasy projections.

5.3.1 Preparing Training and Test Sets¶

One last step before we can actually create our models, we need to divide our data into a training set and a test set. This is necessary because it would not be fair to test our model on data that it trained on. We will also split it up into x and y, where x is our input data, which is only what is available during the game. Y is the points remaining, which is what we are trying to predict with our projections.

5.3.3 Linear Regression with Interaction Terms¶

For our next model, we will use another package called statsmodels, which provides a function called ols, which allows us to perform a linear regression with whichever terms we choose. Here we are going to use all possible interaction terms between our columns. To accomplish this, we will use an R-style formula in our method call. As the number of columns increases, these interactions can get out of hand very quickly. However, since we are only analyzing 5 columns, it is still reasonable to look at all of the interactions.

Read more about:

  • OLS: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/generated/statsmodels.formula.api.ols.html
  • R-style formulas: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/example_formulas.html
In [42]:
# Same process as above but for qbs
train_qb = pd.concat([X_train_qb, y_train_qb], axis=1)
train_qb.rename(columns={0: 'qb_rem_pts'}, inplace=True)
qb_ols = smf.ols(formula='qb_rem_pts ~ qb_total_pts * home_pos * game_seconds_remaining * yardline_100 * home_diff', data=train_qb).fit()
print(qb_ols.summary())

mse = ((qb_ols.predict(X_test_qb) - y_test_qb)**2).mean()
print(f'MSE = {mse}')

The summary features prints out a ton of information about our model, so let's focus on some highlights:

  • This is far more linear regression terms than normal, but it is helpful here because it allows the algorithm to identify correlations that we might not see through typical data exploration.
  • You can see which interaction terms we are confident about a relationship in by the column p > |t|, which is more or less the probability of a significant correlation between that interaction and our results.
  • We have an R-squared value of 0.805, which is not enough for us to say that the correlation is decidedly linear, but it is certainly high for a dataset that on first glance does not seem very linear at all.
  • Our MSE on the test set is 7.477, which is a huge improvement on the base predictions!

6 Conclusion¶

The goal for the project was to create a model for in-game projections that is more accurate than the current model. By all accounts we were were successful in achieving that goal for wide receivers, running backs, and quarterbacks.

Parts of the data engineering were arduous and convoluted, but formatting the data as we did was key in streamlining the creation of our visualizations and models.

In our preliminary data exploration, we could not find any significant trends with one independent variable, but when we extended to analyze the interaction between two independent variables, we were able to find a consequential correlation.

With this in mind, we landed on a linear regression model with interaction terms between all of our input variables that significantly decreased the mean squared error for each of our positions.

If the main fantasy sites were to implement an algorithm like this, it would provide a concrete improvement to the user experience as players can be more confident in the projected numbers of their players. A fantasy site adopting a similar system would result in an advantage over the competition, and could result in fantasy players switching platforms to utilize the improved projections.
